"about 1260","1279":"1279","1300":"1300","Abt 1331":"about 1331","1331":"1331","1230":"1230","1240":"1240","1350":"1350","1282":"1282","1260":"1260","Whitfield Hall,Northumberland, England":"Whitfield, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom","Whitfield Hall,Whitfield,Northumberland, England":"Whitfield, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","Langwathby, Cumberland, England":"Langwathby, Cumberland, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"WHITFIELD","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called Whitfield, for example in Derbyshire, Gloucestershire, Kent, Northamptonshire, and Northumberland, or Whitefield in Lancashire and the Isle of Wight, named with Old English <i>hwīt</i> ‘white’ + <i>feld</i> ‘open country’, probably because of their chalky soil.","History: Henry Whitfield (1597–<i>c.</i> 1657), preacher and scholar, came from Mortlake, Surrey, England (now part of Greater London) to New Haven, CT, in 1639 and was one of the first settlers in Guilford, CT. He had ten children, some of whom he left in CT when he returned to England in 1650, where he died."],"variants":[{"name":"Whitfill","meanings":["English: probably a variant of   Whitfield  ."]},{"name":"Whitefield","meanings":["English: variant of   Whitfield  .","Americanized form of German <b>Weissfeld</b> (see   Weisfeld  )."]}]},{"name":"RICHARD","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When RICHARD WHITFIELD was born about 1260, in Whitfield, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom, his father, ROBERT WHITFIELD, was 32 and his mother, BEATRIX De QUITFIELD, was 22. He had at least 1 son. He died about 1331, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 73."},"et":{"Abt 1260–Abt 1331":"umbes 1260–umbes 1331","1260–1331":"1260–1331","1279–1350":"1279–1350","1230–1282":"1230–1282","1240–1300":"1240–1300","Abt 1260":"umbes 1260","1279":"1279","1300":"1300","Abt 1331":"umbes 1331","1331":"1331","1230":"1230","1240":"1240","1350":"1350","1282":"1282","1260":"1260","Whitfield Hall,Northumberland, England":"Whitfield, Northumberland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Whitfield Hall,Whitfield,Northumberland, England":"Whitfield, Northumberland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Langwathby, Cumberland, England":"Langwathby, Cumberland, England"},"fi":{"Abt 1260–Abt 1331":"noin 1260–noin 1331","1260–1331":"1260–1331","1279–1350":"127